        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-12-08T18:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-12-08T18:00:00-05:00" n="1400" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1400">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">125.7141/11–3049: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Consul General at Peiping</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Clubb</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="49" xml:id="d1400fn49">Repeated to the Embassy at Nanking
                        as No. 1282.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-12-08T18:00:00-05:00">December 8, 1949—6 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>887. Urtel 2155 Nov 30. Because of deadline suggest you inform local Commie auths
                    Peiping properties acquired by “Final protocol for the settlement of the
                    disturbances of 1900” concluded at Peking, Sept 7, 1901 (Art. VII)<note n="50" xml:id="d1400fn50">
                        <ref target="frus1901#pg_312">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, Appendix, 1901, Affairs in
                            China, pp. 312</ref>, <ref target="frus1901#pg_316">316</ref>.</note>
                    and rights thereto confirmed by “Treaty between the United States of America and
                    the Republic of China for the relinquishment of extraterritorial rights in China
                    and the regulation of related matters”, which was signed at Washington Jan 11,
                    1943 and entered into force May 20, 1943 (Art. II).<note n="51" xml:id="d1400fn51">Department of State Treaty Series No. 984, or 57 Stat.
                        (pt. 2) 767, 768.</note> Suggest you concert with colleagues.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Acheson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
